      "h": "Tracing Linguistic Roots",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> The name 'Texas' originates from the Caddo indigenous word 'tejas,' which means 'friends' or 'allies.' Spanish explorers adopted this term, and over time it evolved into the name of the region. The term 'Texican' was formed by adding a Spanish suffix to 'Texas,' signifying a person belonging to or associated with Texas, highlighting the fusion of indigenous and Spanish linguistic elements.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; kids.nationalgeographic.com; everything-everywhere.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>'Texas' derives from the Caddo word 'tejas' meaning 'friends' or 'allies'</li><li>'Texican' combines 'Texas' with Spanish suffix '-ican' indicating belonging</li><li>Reflects indigenous roots and Spanish linguistic influence</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>For instance, Spanish settlers used 'Texican' to describe themselves as inhabitants of Texas, linking their identity to the land and its indigenous heritage.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Reflect on how place names can carry cultural and historical meanings beyond geography.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Do not assume 'Texas' is purely a Spanish word; its indigenous origin is crucial.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; kids.nationalgeographic.com; everything-everywhere.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p>"
