    "id": "slide3",
    "eyebrow": "Cultural Influences",
    "num": "03",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">03</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Cultural Influences</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Indigenous and Colonial Roots of Texican Identity</h2><ul><li>Texican culture influenced by Caddo and other indigenous groups</li><li>Spanish colonial traditions shaped language, religion, and governance</li><li>Mexican rule added new political and cultural layers</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican identity was shaped by the indigenous peoples of the region, especially the Caddo, whose social structures and language influenced early settlers. Spanish colonialism introduced Catholicism, Spanish language, and legal systems. Later Mexican governance brought additional cultural and political changes, creating a layered Texican identity. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texican communities often celebrated Catholic festivals while maintaining indigenous-inspired social customs, illustrating cultural blending.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify examples of how indigenous and colonial cultures might merge in daily life.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Avoid viewing Texican culture as purely Spanish or Mexican; indigenous influence was significant.</p></div></div>",
