    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">04</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Historical Context</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Spanish and Mexican Texas: Setting the Stage</h2><ul><li>Texas was part of Spanish colonial territory until 1821</li><li>Mexican independence brought Texas under Mexican governance</li><li>Texicans lived in a frontier region with diverse populations</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Before becoming part of the United States, Texas was first a Spanish colony and then part of independent Mexico after 1821. Texicans lived in a frontier environment marked by interactions among indigenous peoples, Spanish settlers, Mexican authorities, and Anglo-American immigrants, creating a complex social and political landscape. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texican settlers often negotiated land rights and alliances with indigenous groups while adapting to changing colonial and national governments.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Consider how shifting political control might affect the identity and loyalties of frontier settlers.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Do not assume Texicans were static in their political affiliations; they navigated changing regimes.</p></div></div>",
