    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">07</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Historical Usage</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">How Was 'Texican' Used Historically?</h2><ul><li>Used by settlers to assert local identity in Spanish and Mexican Texas</li><li>Distinguished Hispanic Texans from Anglo settlers and indigenous groups</li><li>Appeared in documents, letters, and official records</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Historical records show 'Texican' used by settlers to express a distinct identity tied to Texas, differentiating themselves from other groups during periods of political change and cultural blending. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Letters from the early 1800s refer to 'Texicans' when discussing local affairs and community matters, emphasizing their unique status.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Review a historical excerpt and identify how 'Texican' is used to convey identity.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Avoid assuming 'Texican' was a universally accepted or uncontested term.</p></div></div>",
