      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texican identity was not fixed; settlers often faced conflicting loyalties during the transition from Spanish to Mexican rule and the Texas Revolution, reflecting the complexity of their cultural and political position.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; kids.nationalgeographic.com; everything-everywhere.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texicans navigated loyalties between Spain, Mexico, and Texas</li><li>Identity was fluid amid political upheaval</li><li>Some Texicans supported independence, others remained loyal</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Some Texicans fought alongside Anglo settlers for Texas independence, while others remained loyal to Mexico.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Discuss how shifting political contexts might influence personal and community identity.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Avoid assuming all Texicans shared the same political views or loyalties.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; kids.nationalgeographic.com; everything-everywhere.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p>"
