    "eyebrow": "Settlement Patterns",
    "num": "13",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">13</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Settlement Patterns</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Early Texican Settlements in Spanish Texas</h2><ul><li>Texicans settled primarily along rivers and fertile lands for farming and ranching</li><li>Communities often formed near missions and presidios for protection</li><li>Settlement patterns reflected Spanish colonial land grant systems</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texicans established settlements in strategic locations such as river valleys and near Spanish missions, which provided both resources and security. These settlements followed Spanish colonial land grant policies, shaping the distribution and size of communities. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> The San Antonio River area became a hub for Texican ranching and farming due to its water access and proximity to the San Antonio de Béxar presidio.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Examine a map of early Texican settlements and identify why certain locations were chosen over others.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming Texican settlements were randomly placed rather than strategically located for resources and defense.</p></div></div>",
