    "num": "14",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">14</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Frontier Lifestyle</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Daily Life and Economy of the Texicans</h2><ul><li>Texicans practiced mixed farming and extensive cattle ranching</li><li>Homes were often simple adobe or wooden structures adapted to frontier conditions</li><li>Community life included religious festivals, markets, and mutual aid</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican daily life combined subsistence farming with cattle ranching, reflecting the frontier environment. Their homes and social structures adapted to available materials and the need for cooperation in isolated settlements. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A typical Texican ranch would raise cattle for hides and meat, while also growing corn and beans for family consumption.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Describe how Texican economic activities supported both survival and trade.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Overlooking the importance of cattle ranching as a key economic driver alongside farming.</p></div></div>",
