    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">15</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Cultural Blending</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Texican Interaction with Indigenous and Other Settlers</h2><ul><li>Texicans blended Spanish, indigenous, and Mexican cultural practices</li><li>Intermarriage and trade with indigenous groups were common</li><li>Shared knowledge of land and survival techniques enhanced adaptation</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican culture was a hybrid, incorporating indigenous customs and Spanish colonial traditions. This blending was evident in language, food, and social practices, facilitating coexistence and mutual benefit. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texican ranchers adopted indigenous techniques for cattle herding and used native plants for food and medicine.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify examples of cultural blending in Texican daily life and explain their significance.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Viewing Texican culture as purely Spanish without recognizing indigenous influences.</p></div></div>",
