    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">29</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Texican Leaders</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Prominent Texican Figures in the Revolution</h2><ul><li>Juan Seguín: Texican military leader and politician</li><li>José Antonio Navarro: Advocate for Texican rights and independence</li><li>Their leadership bridged cultural and political divides</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Key Texican leaders like Juan Seguín and José Antonio Navarro played instrumental roles in the Texas Revolution and early statehood, advocating for Texican interests and navigating complex political landscapes. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Juan Seguín led Texican troops at San Jacinto and later served in the Texas Senate, exemplifying Texican leadership.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Examine how Texican leaders balanced cultural identity with political goals during and after the revolution.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Ignoring the political influence of Texican leaders in favor of Anglo figures.</p></div></div>",
