    "num": "30",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">30</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Texican Cultural Identity</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Cultural Blending and Identity During the Revolution</h2><ul><li>Texicans embodied a blend of Spanish, Mexican, indigenous, and Anglo influences</li><li>Their cultural identity influenced their political and military decisions</li><li>Revolutionary events intensified questions of loyalty and belonging</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">The Texican identity was shaped by a rich cultural blending that influenced how individuals and communities navigated the Texas Revolution. This hybridity created both unity and tension within Texican society. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texican families often practiced Catholicism and spoke Spanish while adopting some Anglo customs, reflecting cultural blending.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Reflect on how cultural identity might complicate political allegiance during conflict.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Oversimplifying Texican identity as solely Mexican or Anglo without recognizing cultural hybridity.</p></div></div>",
