      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> After the revolution, Texicans encountered political challenges as Anglo settlers dominated governance, leading to disputes over rights and identity within the new Republic of Texas.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; kids.nationalgeographic.com; thestoryoftexas.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texicans faced marginalization in new Texan government structures</li><li>Conflicts arose over land rights, citizenship, and cultural recognition</li><li>Some Texicans advocated for inclusion and protection of their communities</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>José Antonio Navarro worked to secure land titles and political representation for Texicans in the Texas legislature.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Analyze how post-revolution political dynamics affected Texican communities.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming Texican political influence remained strong and unchallenged after independence.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; kids.nationalgeographic.com; thestoryoftexas.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p>"
