    "id": "slide34",
    "eyebrow": "Contested Interpretations",
    "num": "34",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">34</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Contested Interpretations</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Debates Over Texican Loyalties and Identity</h2><ul><li>Historians differ on the extent of Texican support for independence</li><li>Some argue Texicans were primarily loyal to Mexico</li><li>Others emphasize their active role in Texas nation-building</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Scholarly debates highlight contested interpretations of Texican loyalties and identity, reflecting the complexity of their historical role and the challenges of limited sources. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Some historians cite Texican participation in battles as evidence of strong independence support, while others point to documented Mexican sympathies.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Evaluate differing historical arguments and form your own interpretation based on evidence.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Accepting one-sided historical narratives without considering alternative viewpoints.</p></div></div>",
