      "h": "Integrating Complex Historical Perspectives",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Reflecting on Texican history encourages learners to appreciate the complexities of identity, loyalty, and historical interpretation in early Texas history.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; kids.nationalgeographic.com; thestoryoftexas.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texican identity was shaped by cultural blending and political challenges</li><li>Their role in the Texas Revolution was complex and multifaceted</li><li>Understanding Texicans requires critical engagement with diverse sources</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Discuss how Texican experiences illustrate broader themes of cultural hybridity and contested nationhood.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Write a brief reflection on how Texican identity challenges simple historical narratives.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Oversimplifying Texican history without acknowledging its contested nature.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; kids.nationalgeographic.com; thestoryoftexas.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p>"
