    "id": "slide37",
    "eyebrow": "Primary Sources Introduction",
    "num": "37",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">37</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Primary Sources Introduction</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Understanding Texican History Through Primary Sources</h2><ul><li>Primary sources offer direct evidence from the Texican era.</li><li>Documents include letters, official records, and artifacts.</li><li>They reveal personal experiences and cultural details.</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Primary sources provide authentic insights into Texican life and history, allowing learners to engage with the voices and materials from the period directly. These sources help overcome gaps and biases in secondary interpretations. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A letter from a Texican settler describing daily life illustrates cultural blending and frontier challenges.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Examine a primary source excerpt and identify what it reveals about Texican identity.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Avoid assuming primary sources are unbiased; consider context and perspective.</p></div></div>",
    "paper": {
      "secnum": "Deep Dive 37",
      "h": "Why Primary Sources Matter for Texican Studies",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Primary sources provide authentic insights into Texican life and history, allowing learners to engage with the voices and materials from the period directly. These sources help overcome gaps and biases in secondary interpretations.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from libguides.tamusa.edu; texasstudies.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Primary sources offer direct evidence from the Texican era.</li><li>Documents include letters, official records, and artifacts.</li><li>They reveal personal experiences and cultural details.</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>A letter from a Texican settler describing daily life illustrates cultural blending and frontier challenges.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Examine a primary source excerpt and identify what it reveals about Texican identity.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Avoid assuming primary sources are unbiased; consider context and perspective.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> libguides.tamusa.edu; texasstudies.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup></p>"
    },
    "words": "wordcloud1-lifestyle"
