      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Artifacts such as tools, clothing, and household items offer physical evidence of Texican lifestyle and cultural influences. These objects help fill gaps left by written sources and reveal everyday practices.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from libguides.uta.edu; guides.library.yale.edu. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Artifacts provide tangible evidence of Texican daily life.</li><li>Items reflect cultural blending and frontier adaptation.</li><li>Material culture complements written records.</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>A Texican saddle shows Spanish design influences adapted for Texas terrain.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Consider how an artifact reflects cultural blending or practical needs.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Do not interpret artifacts without considering historical context.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> libguides.uta.edu; guides.library.yale.edu <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s16\">[16]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s17\">[17]</sup></p>"
