      "secnum": "Deep Dive 48",
      "h": "Integrating Primary Sources into Historical Understanding",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Reflecting on the use of primary sources and contested interpretations prepares learners to appreciate the richness and challenges of Texican history.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from libguides.tamusa.edu; texasstudies.org; libguides.uta.edu. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Primary sources deepen understanding of Texican culture.</li><li>Historical reconstruction requires critical analysis.</li><li>Texican identity is complex and multifaceted.</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Synthesizing letters, documents, and artifacts reveals a Texican identity shaped by cultural blending and political complexity.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Write a brief reflection on how primary sources changed your understanding of Texicans.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Avoid simplistic or one-dimensional views of Texican history.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> libguides.tamusa.edu; texasstudies.org; libguides.uta.edu <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s16\">[16]</sup></p>"
