      "h": "Factors Influencing Texican Political Loyalties",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texican political loyalties during the Texas Revolution were complex and cannot be reduced to simple categories. Understanding this spectrum is key to grasping their historical role.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; facebook.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texicans held varied loyalties: some loyal to Mexico, others to Texas independence</li><li>Loyalties often influenced by local conditions and personal ties</li><li>Political allegiance was not fixed and could shift during conflict</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Some Texicans fought alongside Anglo settlers at the Alamo, while others remained loyal to the Mexican government.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Identify factors that might cause a Texican to change political allegiance during the revolution.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming all Texicans uniformly supported either Mexico or Texas independence.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; facebook.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup></p>"
